<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-roots-of-quadratic-and-cubic-equations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Roots of Quadratic and Cubic Equations</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Solve quadratic and cubic equations graphically
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To discover that the roots of an equation are the points where its graph intersects the x-axis.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Provide graph paper or graphing software. Guide learners to observe the relationship between the equation $y = f(x)$ and the solutions to $f(x) = 0$.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Imagine you are a mathematical detective tasked with finding the "hidden" solutions to equations. Your most powerful tool is the graph.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Solve the equation <m>x^2 - 4 = 0</m>. What values of <m>x</m> make this true?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Look at the graph of <m>y = x^2 - 4</m> below. 
                        </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image label="Graph_activity-quadratic-detective">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-3,-5) grid (3,2);
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (3,0) node[right] {$x$};
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,2) node[above] {$y$};
                                    \draw[blue, thick, domain=-2.5:2.5, smooth] plot (\x, {\x*\x - 4});
                                    \filldraw[red] (-2,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {\textbf{?}};
                                    \filldraw[red] (2,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {\textbf{?}};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>At what coordinates do the red "clue markers" sit?</p></li>
                            <li><p>What is the value of <m>y</m> at these points?</p></li>
                            <li><p>How do the <m>x</m>-coordinates of these points compare to your algebraic solutions from Step 1?</p></li>
                        </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Cracking the Case: Based on your investigation, if you wanted to find the roots of a complex cubic equation like <m>x^3 - 3x^2 + 2 = 0</m>, how could you use a graph of <m>y = x^3 - 3x^2 + 2</m> to find them without doing any hard algebra?
                        </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image label="Graph_activity-cubic-detective">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-2,-3) grid (4,4);
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {$x$};
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-3) -- (0,4) node[above] {$y$};
                                    \draw[red, thick, domain=-1:3.5, smooth] plot (\x, {\x*\x*\x - 3*\x*\x + 2});
                                    \filldraw[blue] (1,0) circle (1.5pt);
                                    \filldraw[blue] (2,0) circle (1.5pt);
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Plot <m>y = x^3 - 3x^2 + 2</m> and see if the points where it crosses the <m>x</m>-axis are indeed solutions to <m>x^3 - 3x^2 + 2 = 0</m>.
                        </p>
                        <image>
                            <latex-image label="Graph_activity-cubic-solution">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-2,-3) grid (4,4);
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {$x$};
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-3) -- (0,4) node[above] {$y$};
                                    \draw[red, thick, domain=-1:3.5, smooth] plot (\x, {\x*\x*\x - 3*\x*\x + 2});
                                    \filldraw[blue] (1,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below] {$x=1$};
                                    \filldraw[blue] (2,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below] {$x=2$};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                            
                        </image>
                    </li>

                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concept of graphical roots for quadratic and cubic equations.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Link the x-intercepts found in the activity to the solutions of the equation <m>f(x) = 0</m>. Explain that "roots" and "zeros" are other names for these solutions.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Visualization:</alert> Emphasize that a quadratic graph (parabola) can have 0, 1, or 2 roots, while a cubic graph can have 1, 2, or 3 roots.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            The <term>roots</term> of an equation <m>f(x) = 0</m> are the <m>x</m>-coordinates of the points where the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> intersects the <m>x</m>-axis (where <m>y = 0</m>).
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Quadratic Equations:</alert> <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>. The roots are found by looking at where the parabola <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> meets the <m>x</m>-axis.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Cubic Equations:</alert> <m>ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d = 0</m>. The roots are found by looking at where the cubic curve <m>y = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d</m> meets the <m>x</m>-axis.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
       <p>
        <alert>How to solve quadratic equations by graphing:</alert>
       </p>
       <p>
          1. Plot the parabola defined by the quadratic function.
       </p>
         <p>
           2. Identify the points where the parabola intersects the x-axis.
         </p>
            <p>
               3. The x-coordinates of these intersection points are the roots of the quadratic equation.
            </p>
             <p>
                <alert>How to solve cubic equations by graphing:</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                1. Plot the cubic curve defined by the cubic function.
                </p>
                <p>
                2. Identify the points where the cubic curve intersects the x-axis.
                </p>
                <p>
                3. The x-coordinates of these intersection points are the roots of the cubic equation.
                </p>
                 
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the equation <m>x^2 - 2x - 3 = 0</m> graphically.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let <m>y = x^2 - 2x - 3</m>. We create a table of values:
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell>-2</cell>
                    <cell>-1</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                    <cell>3</cell>
                    <cell>4</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell>5</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>-3</cell>
                    <cell>-4</cell>
                    <cell>-3</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>5</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                Plotting these points gives the following parabola:
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-roots-quadratic" width="50%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-3,-5) grid (5,6);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,6) node[above] {$y$};
                        \draw[blue, thick, domain=-1.5:3.5, smooth] plot (\x, {\x*\x - 2*\x - 3});
                        \filldraw (-1,0) circle (2pt) node[above left] {$x=-1$};
                        \filldraw (3,0) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$x=3$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                The graph intersects the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 3</m>. 
                Therefore, the roots of <m>x^2 - 2x - 3 = 0</m> are <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 3</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the cubic equation <m>x^3 - 3x + 1 = 0</m> graphically for <m>-2.5 \le x \le 2.5</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let <m>y = x^3 - 3x + 1</m>. We plot the curve:
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-roots-cubic" width="60%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-3,-4) grid (3,4);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (3,0) node[right] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,4) node[above] {$y$};
                        \draw[red, thick, domain=-2.1:2.1, smooth] plot (\x, {\x*\x*\x - 3*\x + 1});
                        \filldraw (-1.88,0) circle (1.5pt);
                        \filldraw (0.35,0) circle (1.5pt);
                        \filldraw (1.53,0) circle (1.5pt);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                From the graph, the curve crosses the <m>x</m>-axis at three points. Approximating from the grid:
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>x \approx -1.9</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>x \approx 0.3</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>x \approx 1.5</m></p></li>
                </ul>
                These are the roots of the equation <m>x^3 - 3x + 1 = 0</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the roots of <m>x^2 - 4x + 4 = 0</m> graphically.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Plotting <m>y = x^2 - 4x + 4</m>:
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-roots-repeated" width="40%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-1,-1) grid (5,5);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};
                        \draw[blue, thick, domain=0:4, smooth] plot (\x, {\x*\x - 4*\x + 4});
                        \filldraw (2,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {$x=2$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                The graph touches the <m>x</m>-axis at only one point, <m>(2, 0)</m>. 
                This means the equation <m>x^2 - 4x + 4 = 0</m> has one repeated root, <m>x = 2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>   
                <p>
                    The graph of <m>y = x^2 + k</m> is shown below. If the graph does not cross the <m>x</m>-axis, what can you say about the roots of the equation <m>x^2 + k = 0</m>?
                </p>
                <image width="40%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (2,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,3) node[above] {$y$};
                            \draw[blue, thick, domain=-1.5:1.5] plot (\x, {\x*\x + 1});
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>   
            <solution>
                <p>
                    If the graph does not intersect the <m>x</m>-axis, the equation has no real roots.
                </p>
            </solution>             
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the equation <m>x^3 - x^2 - 2x = 0</m> by plotting the graph of <m>y = x^3 - x^2 - 2x</m> for <m>-2 \le x \le 3</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Factoring <m>y = x(x^2 - x - 2) = x(x - 2)(x + 1)</m>. 
                    The graph crosses the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x = -1, x = 0,</m> and <m>x = 2</m>.
                    These are the roots of the equation.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use a graph to estimate the roots of <m>x^2 - 5 = 0</m>. (Hint: Plot <m>y = x^2 - 5</m>).
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The roots are <m>x = \pm \sqrt{5}</m>. Graphically, these are approximately <m>x \approx -2.2</m> and <m>x \approx 2.2</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Focus on quadratic equations first. Use technology (like Desmos) to visualize how shifting a graph vertically changes the number of roots.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Practice plotting both quadratic and cubic functions accurately to read roots from the graph.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Explore the relationship between the coefficients of a cubic equation and the number of real roots. Investigate "turning points" and how they relate to the existence of roots.
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/reflection.ptx"/>
</section>

